NATO head Anders Fogh Rasmussen refused to see Moscow's moves as bringing a solution to the crisis. 

Through its actions in Ukraine, Russia 'has broken the rules and eroded the trust,' he said.

It is Moscow's 'illegal actions in Ukraine which pose a threat to the international order'.

NATO has accused Russia of increasing its troop numbers close to Ukraine's borders and proving weaponry and fighters to rebel forces.

'Today, we see no changes in Russia's behaviour. So we have no options but to maintain the suspension of practical civilian and military cooperation. '

'There will be no business as usual with Russia until Russia comes back into line with its international obligations.'

On military exercises in Russia this week, forces are conducting drills in 'peacekeeping' tasks. 

